# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cibi
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cibi/1976-fiji-rugby-union-tour-of-australia] The **1976 Fiji rugby union tour of Australia** was a series of matches played between May and June 1976 by the Fiji national rugby union team in Australia.
[src:cibi/1976-fiji-rugby-union-tour-of-australia] Three tests were played, all won by the Wallabies.
[src:cibi/1980-fiji-rugby-union-tour-of-argentina] The **1980 Fiji rugby union tour of Argentina** was a series of matches played between October and November by the Fiji national rugby union team in Argentina.
[src:cibi/1980-fiji-rugby-union-tour-of-argentina] It was the first visit of a rugby union team from Polynesia to Argentina.
[src:cibi/1984-fiji-rugby-union-tour-of-australia] The **1984 Fiji rugby union tour of Australia** was a series of matches played between March and April 1984 by Fiji national rugby union team in Australia.
[src:cibi/1985-fiji-rugby-union-tour-of-british-isles] The **1985 Fiji rugby union tour of British Isles** was a series of matches played in October 1985 in Wales, Ireland, and England by the Fiji national rugby union team.
[src:cibi/1989-fiji-rugby-union-tour-of-oceania] The **1989 Fiji rugby union tour of Oceania** was a series of matches played in Australia, New Zealand, Samoa and Tonga, between April and June 1989 in by Fiji national rugby union team.
[src:cibi/1989-fiji-rugby-union-tour-of-oceania] In reality there were three different tours.
[src:cibi/1989-fiji-rugby-union-tour-of-oceania] In April in Australia, then in New Zealand (no test match) and in June–July in Samoa and Tonga.
[src:cibi/cibi] The **Cibi** (Fijian pronunciation: [ˈðimbi] *DHIM-bee*) is a Fijian meke of Bauan origin and war dance, generally performed before or after a battle.
[src:cibi/cibi] It came to prominence in the rugby field in 1939 when it was performed by the Fiji national rugby union team before the match.
[src:cibi/cibi] It is also known as **Teivovo** ("war fence", from *tei voavoa*, 'planting on abandoned land').
[src:cibi/cibi] The origins of the cibi date back to the country's warring times with their Pacific neighbours and intertribal warfare.
[src:cibi/cibi] On their return home the warriors heralded their victory by displaying flags – one for every enemy slain.
[src:cibi/cibi] They were met by the women who would sing songs with accompanying gestures.
[src:cibi/cibi] The cibi was meant for open battle to inspire the troops, but it was sung with more vigour when the victorious army returned home to celebrate.
[src:cibi/cibi] In 1939, when Fiji prepared for its first-ever tour of New Zealand, the captain, Ratu Sir George Cakobau, thought his team should have a war dance to match the All Blacks' haka.
[src:cibi/cibi] He approached Ratu Bola, the high chief of the warrior clan of Navusaradave in Bau, who taught them the Cibi which has been adopted as Fiji's pre-match ritual ever since and went on to become the only team to remain unbeaten on a full tour of New Zealand.
[src:cibi/cibi] The *cibi* had perhaps been used incorrectly though, as the word actually means "a celebration of victory by warriors", "a dance of triumph" whereas *bole* or *ibole* is the acceptance of a challenge.
[src:cibi/cibi] For this reason, the Cibi was replaced in 2012 with the new Bole (pronounced [ˈᵐbole] *mbo-lay*) war cry.
[src:cibi/cibi] The Bole war cry has a lot more energy compared to the Cibi and seems far more fitting for the gruelling match that is about to commence, However, after the 2012 Pacific Nations Rugby Cup, the Cibi returned to be used.
[src:cibi/cibi] The Bole however has not been used after the 2012 Pacific Nations Rugby Cup match against Tonga.
[src:cibi/cibi] The Flying Fijians have opted to use the Cibi for the rest of their matches.
[src:cibi/cibi] The current reason for the team removing the Bole is unknown.
[src:cibi/ote-a] The **ʻōteʻa** (usually written as *otea*) is a traditional dance and accompanying music from Tahiti characterized by a rapid hip-shaking motion to percussion accompaniment.
[src:cibi/ote-a] The dancers, standing in several rows, may be further choreographed to execute different figures (including tamau, varu, otamu, ami, and fa'arapu) while maintaining the hip-shaking.
[src:cibi/ote-a] The hip motion itself may in some choreographies be synchronized amongst multiple dancers and may be further coordinated with the accompanying percussion arrangement.
[src:cibi/ote-a] The dance is with music only (drums) at a fast rhythm, and no singing.
[src:cibi/ote-a] The drum can be one of the different types of the *tōʻere*, a lying log of wood with a longitudinal slit, which is struck by one or two sticks.
[src:cibi/ote-a] Additional drum types accompanying the dance may include the ng drum covered with a shark skin and struck by the hands or with sticks) played at a slower rhythm, or the smaller *faʻatētē* drum.
[src:cibi/ote-a] The ʻōteʻa is one of the few dances which already existed in pre-European times as a male dance.
[src:cibi/ote-a] (The *hura* (Tahitian vernacular for hula), a dance for women, on the other hand has disappeared, and likewise is gone the couple's dance ʻupaʻupa but which may have reemerged as the tāmūrē).
[src:cibi/ote-a] Nowadays, however the ʻōteʻa can be danced by men (ʻōteʻa tāne), by women (ʻōteʻa vahine), or by both genders (ʻōteʻa ʻāmui = united ʻō.).
[src:cibi/ote-a] Dancers of the ʻōteʻa make gestures reenacting daily occupations of life.
[src:cibi/ote-a] For the men the gestural themes can be chosen from warfare or sailing, and then they may use spears or paddles.
[src:cibi/ote-a] For women the gestural themes are typically closer to home or from nature: hand gestures suggesting combing their hair, or the flight of a butterfly.
[src:cibi/ote-a] More elaborate themes have been adopted; for example one where the dancers end up in a map of Tahiti, highlighting important places.
[src:cibi/ote-a] In a proper ʻōteʻa the story of the theme should pervade the whole dance.
[src:cibi/ote-a] The costumes are extremely elaborate, typically incorporating long plant fiber ("grass") skirts, belting with tassels that accentuate the hip-motion, may further include decorated headpieces, and may be color-coordinated across the dancers of the company.
[src:cibi/ote-a] The same *more* dress and the same shaking of the knees for the boys and of the hips for the girls as in all Tahitian dances (see tāmūrē) is used here too.
[src:cibi/ote-a] Interpretations of the **ʻōteʻa** are frequently included as part of larger Polynesian dance recitals presented at luaus and visitor-oriented live shows in the Hawaiian Islands and other Pacific-rim resorts outside Tahiti.
[src:cibi/ote-a] Modern drum accompaniments may include drums of European or non-Pacific construction, improvised percussion instruments of modern materials (e.g. high-density polyethylene or metallic commercial food packaging), and the use of prerecorded drum reinforcement soundtracks.
[src:cibi/upa-upa] The **ʼupaʼupa** (often written as **upa upa**) is a traditional dance from Tahiti.
[src:cibi/upa-upa] It was mentioned by European explorers, who described it as very indecent.
[src:cibi/upa-upa] It is not quite clear how similar the gestures at that time were with the now immensely popular tāmūrē.
[src:cibi/upa-upa] In both dances the performers form groups of pairs of a boy and a girl, dancing more or less in sexually oriented movements.
[src:cibi/upa-upa] The musical setting usually includes voice, flute, and drums.
[src:cibi/upa-upa] After having arrived on Tahiti in 1797, the LMS missionaries quickly intimidated the local rulers of the island and fixed themselves in a position of power.
[src:cibi/upa-upa] Although this enabled them to abolish such habits as infanticide, cannibalism and tribal wars, it also enabled them to introduce the idea of sin, which was unknown on Tahiti until then.
[src:cibi/upa-upa] The joy of dancing, so dear to the Polynesian heart, was one of the first to be axed.
[src:cibi/upa-upa] The famous Pōmare code of 1819 declared the ʼupaʼupa (and tattooing in the same line) to be bad and immoral habitudes, severely to be opposed.
[src:cibi/upa-upa] In the code of 1842 many restrictions were relaxed, but the ʼupaʼupa (the general term for dancing then) remained on the black list.
[src:cibi/upa-upa] In the same year the French proclaimed the protectorate.
[src:cibi/upa-upa] Being Catholic with some broader views on life than the Protestants, and considering that "if you cannot beat them, join them", they proclaimed in the official bulletin of 1849 that the ʼupaʼupa was still forbidden, except on public feastdays, but then still without the indecent gestures.
[src:cibi/upa-upa] The act of 1853, repeated in 1876 was more restrictive.
[src:cibi/upa-upa] In the hope that the Tahitians would spend their time on more pious occupations than dancing and drinking, a system of licenses was introduced.
[src:cibi/upa-upa] A license could only be obtained by a chef and only on Saturday evenings.
[src:cibi/upa-upa] Despite all these restrictions, dancing went on, less secret or more secret depending on the law at that moment.
[src:cibi/upa-upa] Nevertheless, many years of suppression had left a mark on it, and although the idea and the steps were still there, the ʼupaʼupa of the old did not really exist anymore.
[src:cibi/upa-upa] In the beginning of the 20th century Tahitian dances were only performed on such festivities as 14 July and saw an evolution into what they have become nowadays.
[src:cibi/upa-upa] Around 1900 the traditional costumes came back, and although they still looked more like mother Hubbard dresses or ponchos, at least they were made of traditional materials.
[src:cibi/upa-upa] Around 1920 strips of raffia were added, which soon would develop into the characteristic *more* or grass skirt (in reality made from hibiscus fibers) of Tahiti.
[src:cibi/upa-upa] The bare torso (for men only) became acceptable.
[src:cibi/upa-upa] Prizes started to be awarded to the best dancers on a festival.
[src:cibi/upa-upa] But it was not until 1956 that Madeleine Mouʼa organised a dance group, called the *heiva*, of which Teriʼi and Takau, daughters of the last queen of Tahiti became patrons.
[src:cibi/upa-upa] Finally then traditional dancing had the blessing from the establishment.
[src:cibi/upa-upa] The opening of Faaʼa International Airport in 1961 and the real start of the tourist industry on Tahiti made all the dances which had come forth from the ʼupaʼupa a part of daily life once more.
